<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S., DPRK Discuss Inspections, DPRK Letter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S., DPRK Discuss Inspections, DPRK Letter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0905231794 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2208 GMT 9 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0905231794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The United States and North Korea held a 
working-level contact in New York early this morning, Korean 
time, and discussed additional inspections [chuga sachal], 
including the inspection related to the replacement of fuel rods. 
  Gary Samore, chief of the Nuclear Nonproliferation 
Department 
of the State Department, and Kenneth Quinones, the official in 
charge of North Korean affairs, represented the U.S. side, and 
Han Song-yol, counselor at the North Korean UN Mission, and 
(Hyon Hak-pong), secretary at the mission, represented the North 
Korean side at the contact. 
  Today's contact took place for the United States to deliver 
its reply to the 5 May letter from Kang Sok-chu, first vice 
foreign minister of North Korea. The United States reportedly 
notified North Korea that no further dialogue would be possible 
if an International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] inspection team 
were not allowed to carry out appropriate inspection activities 
[chokchorhan sachal hwaltong]. However, the United States 
reportedly asked North Korea to quickly reach an agreement with 
the IAEA over technological problems concerning additional 
inspections, hold the third round of U.S.-North Korea talks, and 
resolve the nuclear issue quickly without breaking the UN 
Security Council's tentative deadline of mid-May, thus, strongly 
hinting that it intends to resume working-level talks. 

</TEXT>

