<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   SRV Said To Oppose DPRK Nuclear Development </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SRV Said To Oppose DPRK Nuclear Development </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1005034894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0255 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1005034894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 10 (YONHAP) -- The Vietnamese Government 
has informed South Korean lawmakers of its official position 
that it opposes North Korea's nuclear development program, the 
chairman of the National Assembly Foreign Affairs and National 
Unification Committee said Tuesday. 
  Chairman Chong Chae-mun and five other committee members 
visited Vietnam from May 2-7. Chong, speaking to reporters 
about his tour of the Southeast Asian country, said, "the 
Vietnamese leaders made clear that nuclear weapons should not 
exist on the Korean peninsula and even though Vietnam has a 
communist system like North Korea, it does not support North 
Korea's lines." 
  On the unification issue, Chong quoted Vietnam's leaders as 
saying that South and North Korea will eventually accomplish 
reunification through peaceful dialogue. 
  During their trip the Korean lawmakers met with senior 
Vietnamese leaders, including former Chief Secretary of the 
Communist Party Nguyen Van Linh, House Speaker Nong Duc Manh and 
First Deputy Prime Minister Pham Van Khai, and discussed 
expanding economic cooperation, supporting children fathered by 
Koreans, locating Korean soldiers lost during the Vietnam war 
and returning the remains of Korean soldiers. 
  Also visiting Hanoi were Reps. Pak Chong-su and Kim Tong-kun 
of the ruling Democratic Liberal Party, Pak Sil and Chin 
Nam-kung of the opposition Democratic Party and independent Yi 
Chong-chan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

