<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Europeans Press for Wider Access to Auto Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Europeans Press for Wider Access to Auto Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0905063594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0612 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0905063594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 9 (YONHAP) -- The Europeans are playing 
hardball with Korean automakers by threatening to strip them of 
their Generalized System of Preferences (GSP) status for car 
imports. 
  The European Union (EU) is reacting sensitively to Korea's 
fast advancement into its market, a Foreign Ministry official 
said Monday. 
  The ACEA (Association of European Automobile Manufacturers) 
recently submitted a recommendation to the European commission 
urging it to lift GSP privileges for Korean car imports. 
  The ACEA, joined by such major European automakers as Fiat 
of 
Italy, Renault of France and Rover of Britain, also asked for an 
anti-dumping investigation of Korean car exporters in the 
recommendation. 
  Korea exported 90,000 cars to Europe last year while 
importing 500 units. The European Union has repeatedly called 
on Seoul to rectify the trade imbalance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

