<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Livestock Group To Develop Pastures in China </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Livestock Group To Develop Pastures in China </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1005125994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1200 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1005125994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 10 (YONHAP) -- The Livestock Cooperatives 
Federation has decided to develop pasture lands in China as part 
of its plan to explore livestock resources abroad. 
  As an initial step, the federation sent on Tuesday a 
fact-finding team to the three Northeastern Chinese Provinces -- 
Heilongjiang, Liaoning and Jilin -- to determine the feasibility 
of creating pasture lands there. 
  The team will also sound out the possibility of bringing in 
the 1.5 million tons of corn South Korea introduces from China 
annually for use as livestock feeds, directly from China instead 
of through third countries like Hong Kong as now. 
  Overseas development of pasture lands is needed as there is 
no room to expand pasturage in the country and hay fodder prices 
are higher in Korea than those of grain feeds, a federation 
official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

