<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese, Russian Governors Hold Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese, Russian Governors Hold Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1005113894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1114 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1005113894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 10 KYODO -- Japanese and Russian 
governors meeting in Tokyo were at odds Tuesday [10 May] on how 
to refer in a planned joint statement to a long-standing 
territorial dispute over four Russian-held islands off Hokkaido, 
Japanese officials said. Tokyo Gov. Shunichi Suzuki said the 
Japanese delegation wants to incorporate a paragraph on Japan's 
demand for the return of Kunashiri, Etorofu, Shikotan and the 
Habomai group of islets. 
  However, the Russian delegation refused the request, 
pointing 
to an estimated 8,000 cases of territorial violations by 
Japanese fishing boats near the southern Kurils in 1993 alone. 
  Both sides will study further the wording of the statement, 
Suzuki said. 
  Twelve governors headed by Moscow Gov. Anatoliy Styazhlov 
and 
17 governors and vice governors from Japan are discussing 
measures to expand bilateral trade and other relations at the 
13th conference, which opened earlier in the day and will run 
through Thursday next week. 
  Styazhlov told participants that Russia will have to dispel 
fears about political and social instability if it is to 
convince hesitant Japanese companies to join in exploiting the 
country's rich natural resources. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

