<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI To Promote Quality Control in ASEAN </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MITI To Promote Quality Control in ASEAN </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0805122794 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 3 May 94 
Morning Edition p 11--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0805122794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Agency of Industrial Science and Technology 
under the Ministry of International Trade and Industry [MITI] 
will start transferring know-how on Japan's quality control 
(total quality management = TQM) to ASEAN nations as part of 
economic cooperation programs. The TQM system, known as an 
efficient way of improving product quality, has made unique 
development in Japan through pan-corporate quality control (QC) 
circle campaigns. Plans of support for individual ASEAN nations 
will be worked out in 1994 and then be put into practice for 
five years from fiscal 1995. 
  Specifically, 1) manuals on quality improvement will be 
prepared; 2) Japanese experts will be sent to the ASEAN nations 
for on-the-job training; 3) foreign students will be invited for 
training in Japan; and 4) seminars will be held. MITI will soon 
start coordinating requests from those nations, and will decide 
how much time should be given to which industrial areas, for 
instance. 
  At a meeting held between the six ASEAN economic ministers 
and then MITI Minister Hiroshi Kumagai in Singapore last 
October, an agreement was reached on action plans to promote 
industrial development in the ASEAN nations. The action plans 
included "the promotion of industrial standardization and 
quality control for improvement of product quality." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

