<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Early Diet Approval of Revised SDF Law Expected </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Early Diet Approval of Revised SDF Law Expected </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105054394 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1105054394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In view of the fact that a state of emergency has 
been declared in Yemen, the government now holds growing 
expectations for the early approval of the Self-Defense Force 
[SDF] Law revision so the SDF can be mobilized to rescue 
Japanese residing abroad. This issue was shelved for further 
deliberations at the last Diet session. Since the outbreak of 
the civil war in Yemen, the safety of Japanese residing there 
cannot be assured. Under the current situation, however, the 
Japanese Government is incapable of helping them to flee the 
country but has to rely on other countries. For example, they 
will have "to take advantage of" vacancies on military aircraft 
or vessels of other countries. And it is believed the 
government has also taken into consideration the situation when 
overseas Japanese have to be rescued in case of economic 
sanctions against the DPRK (North Korea). 
  With regard to Japanese residing in Yemen, the government 
issued recommendations for evacuation on 9 May. However, since 
the government cannot mobilize the SDF or government aircraft 
for the rescue operation, a total of 70 Japanese -- as reported 
by the Foreign Ministry -- have sought safety in such places as 
Djibouti in Africa by U.S., German and Italian military aircraft 
or French military vessels. 
  In this connection, Administrative Vice Foreign Minister 
Kunihiko Saito stressed at a news conference on 9 May that the 
SDF Law has to be revised at an early date. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

