<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Support Reported for SDPJ Break From Coalition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Support Reported for SDPJ Break From Coalition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1205001694 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 11 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1205001694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to a recent nationwide opinion poll 
conducted by ASAHI SHIMBUN on 8 and 9 May, 53 percent of 
respondents said "it was appropriate" for the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ] to leave the coalition administration, 
while 26 percent said "it was not appropriate." Thus, the 
approval rate of the SDPJ's decision was much higher than the 
disapproval rate. Among the respondents who support the SDPJ, 
57 percent highly evaluated the party's secession from the 
coalition while 29 percent were critical of the secession. 
  In terms of party affiliation, it is noteworthy that 76 
percent of supporters for the Japan Communist Party [JCP] 
welcomed the SDPJ's secession from the coalition. Next to this 
figure, 67 percent of Sakigake [Harbinger] supporters and 57 
percent of Liberal Democratic Party supporters welcomed the 
SDPJ's action. 
  On the other hand, disapproval of the SDPJ's secession was 
conspicuously noted among supporters for the ruling coalition 
parties of the Tsutomu Hata cabinet. For example, the SDPJ's 
secession from the coalition was criticized by 42 percent of 
Democratic Socialist Party supporters, by 41 percent of Komeito 
supporters, and by 36 percent of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] 
supporters. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-52584 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas092__a94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-092-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mirai Party Chief Kano Discusses Party Stance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mirai Party Chief Kano Discusses Party Stance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105130494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1105130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Michihiko Kano, representative of New Party </F>
Mirai, by an unidentified NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN reporter; date 
and place not given] 
  [Text] [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Does your party plan to 
participate in the new parliamentary group "Kaishin"? 
  [Kano] The Japan New Party and the Democratic Socialist 
Party [DSP] have asked us about it. Their thinking that reform 
should be carried out in all areas is essentially the same as 
ours. But we consider procedural matters as being important, 
too. We would like to make a decision after hearing views of 
parties concerned. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] At least, do you intend to 
participate in the decisionmaking bodies of the coalition 
parties -- like the representatives' conference? 
  [Kano] The nine-item basic policies agreed to by the 
coalition parties conform to our line of thinking. We would 
like to offer our efforts in pushing for the policies. We will 
participate in the decisionmaking bodies, if asked. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How do you view the moves being made 
by the Liberal Democratic Party [LDP] and the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ] toward collaborating with each other? 
  [Kano] With the international community in a period of 
change, we must walk the way of reform. We cannot move 
backward. We must realize why we wanted to carry out political 
reform to begin with. What I want to do is to pursue this goal 
based on common policy ideals. People who want to be 
politicians must think about this point. That is the 
responsibility of politicians toward the people. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] If the LDP and the SDPJ decide to 
collaborate, they will be able to carry a no-confidence motion 
in the cabinet, too. 
  [Kano] Their collaboration must not be an illicit union. 
Both parties said so themselves. That is what I want to say to 
them. We must recall why political reform was necessary. We 
must push our policy from a new position. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] There are people saying the House of 
Representatives should be dissolved once the budget is passed. 
  [Kano] The next general election should be held under a new 
election system since the Political Reform Bill has been passed. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How do you intend to expand the force 
of your party in the future? 
  [Kano] We will make efforts to have our party's position and 
basic thinking understood better. There are people who have 
actively sought political reform. We hope we will succeed in 
gaining understanding from a larger number of people. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] There are all kinds of stories now 
circulating about your New Party Mirai. Some say it is leaning 
toward Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], and some say the Mirai 
members defected from the LDP because of problems they had with 
their constituencies. 
  [Kano] I am aware that there are many rumors. But our 
actions are based on the belief that we should go for reform and 
act future-oriented. We cannot stake our political lives only 
on the human relationship. I hope you will understand the 
sincere resolve each of us made in taking the action of bolting 
the LDP and forming the new party and thus risking our own 
political lives. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] What is your position on the taxation 
sytem reform? 
  [Kano] It is part of economic reform, and the question lies 
in how best the assets, consumption, and income levies can be 
balanced. There is also the question of how the direct taxes and 
indirect taxes should be proportioned. It is important that we 
all discuss the matter frankly. In reviewing the matter, we 
will have to think about the future picture of Japan, too. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Do you think an increase in the 
consumption tax rate would be unavoidable? 
  [Kano] The question is not whether to raise that tax, but 
why we must think about it. The vision for the future, the 
standard of lives for the people -- these things need to be 
thought out. We will have to think about the taxation system 
reform, thinking about all these things. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-52585 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas092__a94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-092-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Koshiro Ishida on Political Reform, Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Koshiro Ishida on Political Reform, Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105131894 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 9 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1105131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Koshiro Ishida, director general of the </F>
Management and Coordination Agency and Komeito chairman, by an 
unidentified YOMIURI SHIMBUN reporter; place and date not given] 
  [Text] [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] How will secession of the Social 
Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] from the coalition affect an 
administrative reform program? 
  [Ishida] When the former cabinet decided on a midterm 
administrative reform outline, cabinet ministers from the SDPJ 
were also among those who agreed on it. SDPJ Chairman Murayama 
also said the party will take responsibility for what it is 
responsible for. Thus, the SDPJ has to fulfill its 
responsibility for administrative reform. As for deregulation, 
the government plans to submit 40 relevant bills to the Diet as 
one package during the current session. As for the information 
disclosure system, the government will ask the administrative 
reform committee, which will soon be established, to fully 
discuss the establishment of the system and its legislation. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] The Hata cabinet is called "a cabinet led 
by Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] and Komeito." 
  [Ishida] It was inevitable for Prime Minister Hata to give 
many cabinet posts to these two parties. But we do not need to 
feel so badly about it. The important thing is for the 
government to administer state affairs by placing emphasis on 
its policies. Tax reform is also a demand from society. The 
government has to promote reform while hearing opinions of the 
opposition parties. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Does Komeito plan to participate in the 
new parliamentary group Kaishin [Innovation]? 
  [Ishida] I think our party should consider joining the group 
and fully discuss it. From now on, each party should work to 
reorganize the existing parties into two forces. Otherwise, 
small parties will be defeated in the general election to be 
held under a single-seat constituency system. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Do you think there is a possibility that 
the next general election following the dissolution of the lower 
house will be held under the current multiple-seat constituency 
system. 
  [Ishida] Some people have said it is inevitable to hold the 
general election under the multiple-seat system. This opinion 
is problematic because if the election is held under the current 
system, political reform will be delayed for two or three years. 
The people will never allow such a delay. We should deal with 
this issue after enacting at an early date the bills on new 
constituency boundaries for the single-seat electoral system. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] The chief cabinet secretary said it is 
possible that the general election will be held in July under 
the new electoral system and without a period needed to make the 
new system known to the public. 
  [Ishida] Unlike the past, there are many news organizations 
covering political affairs. I think what he said is possible if 
the government informs the people of the new system through the 
news media. 

</TEXT>

