<H4>    Senior Finance Official Comments </H4>

<F P=102> OW1205103894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1025 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1205103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 12 KYODO -- Japan opposes moves by 
Russia to join the Group of Seven (G-7) economic powers, a 
senior Finance Ministry official said Thursday [12 May]. The 
official, who requested anonymity, said, "It is difficult for 
both donors and a recipient nation like Russia to sit at the 
same table." 
  The official was responding to a news report that said 
President Boris Yeltsin hoped Russia will be allowed to join the 
G-7 group of industrialized nations. He made the remarks at a 
news conference with [the] German chancellor in Bonn. 
  "Japan expects Russia to play a big role in resolving the 
Bosnia issue. Yeltsin seems to be pandering to domestic 
considerations in trying to show that Russia is a strong country 
and a big power," the finance official said. 

</TEXT>

